{{Han etym}}
The word "four" was written as {{zh-l|*亖}} before {{w|Western Zhou}} and {{zh-l|*四}} appeared in late {{w|Spring and Autumn period}}. This alternative form was used to prevent confusion of {{zh-l|*亖}} and {{zh-l|*二}} or {{zh-l|*三}} in vertical writing. It was standardized in {{w|Qin dynasty}}.

The bronzeware style of the character featured a repositioning of those four lines inside {{zh-l|*口}}; this later evolved into the combination used today of {{zh-l|*口|mouth}} and {{zh-l|*八|divide}} which meant ''a dispersal of breath''. It could thus be said that [[four]] is a borrowed meaning for this character. The original sense is preserved in {{och-l|呬}}, by adding an extra {{lang|zh|口}}.

